The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Airline merger clears last hurdle

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 New Delhi, Aug. 24: The Centre today completed the merger of state-run carriers Air India and Indian Airlines. 

 With a fleet of 112 Boeing and Airbus planes, the new entity will be called National Aviation Company of India Limited and will fly under the Air India brand name.

 Officials said the notification, which gives a legal seal to the merger, had been issued. The cabinet approved the merger in March. 

 Air Indias chief V. Thulasidas will head the new airline, while Indian Airlines chairman Vishwapati Trivedi is the joint managing director of the new company. The merged airline will also have a fully owned cargo subsidiary. 

 Overall, over Rs 800cr of annual synergies are expected to be realised once the integration is completed, officials said. 

 The combined turnover of the airlines at the end of 2006 was about Rs 14,700 crore. However, profit was a mere Rs 58 crore, with the lions share generated by Indian Airlines.

 Star Alliance

 The merged airline is set to join the Star Alliance, a global network of 19 carriers. Civil aviation minister Praful Patel said talks on joining the Alliance were at an advanced stage. They (Air India) are keen that they join a major alliance and are in advanced talks with Star Alliance, he said. 




